# Closure in Java

## What is Closure?

-> A Closure is a function/lambda that remembers and uses variables from its outer scope.

-> Even after the outer method finishes execution, the lambda/function can still access those variables.

-> In Java, closures are mainly implemented using:
-> Lambda Expressions
-> Anonymous Inner Classes

-> Closure is commonly used in:
-> Functional Programming
-> Streams API
-> Multithreading
-> Event Handling
-> Callback Functions

---

# Simple Definition

-> A Closure is a lambda or function that captures variables from its surrounding scope and remembers them later.

---

# Why the Name “Closure”?

-> The lambda "closes over" the outer variable.

-> It captures the variable and keeps it available even after the outer method ends.

---

# Basic Example

```java
interface Printer {
    void print();
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int number = 10;

        Printer p = () -> {
            System.out.println(number);
        };

        p.print();
    }
}
```

Output:

```text
10
```

---

# Understanding the Example

```java
int number = 10;
```

-> number is a local variable of the outer method.

```java
Printer p = () -> {
    System.out.println(number);
};
```

-> Lambda is using the outer variable 'number'.

-> Lambda captures the variable.

-> This captured behavior is called Closure.

---

# Internal Flow

```text
Outer Variable Created
        ↓
Lambda Captures Variable
        ↓
Lambda Remembers Variable
        ↓
Lambda Uses Variable Later
```

---

# Real-Life Analogy

-> Suppose a mother gives a lunch box to her child.

-> Even after the child leaves home, the child still has access to the lunch box.

-> Similarly:

```text
Outer Method Ends
        ↓
Lambda Still Remembers Variable
```

