# Another Important Example

```java
public class Main {

    public static Runnable demo() {

        int value = 100;

        return () -> {
            System.out.println(value);
        };
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Runnable r = demo();

        r.run();
    }
}
```

Output:

```text
100
```

---

# Important Observation

-> The demo() method already finished execution.

-> Normally local variables disappear after method completion.

-> But lambda still remembers:

```java
value
```

-> This is Closure behavior.

---

# Why Java Allows This?

-> Java internally captures and stores a copy of the variable.

-> The lambda keeps access to that copied value.

---

# Important Rule in Java

## Captured Variables Must Be Final or Effectively Final

---

# What is Final Variable?

```java
final int x = 10;
```

-> Value cannot be changed.

---

# What is Effectively Final?

-> Variable is not declared final.

-> But value is never modified after assignment.

---

# Example of Effectively Final

```java
int x = 10;

Runnable r = () -> {
    System.out.println(x);
};
```

-> x is effectively final.

-> Code works correctly.

---

# Invalid Example

```java
int x = 10;

x++;

Runnable r = () -> {
    System.out.println(x);
};
```

Compilation Error:

```text
Local variable x defined in an enclosing scope must be final or effectively final
```

---

# Why This Restriction Exists?

-> Local variables are stored in Stack Memory.

-> Stack memory is destroyed after method execution.

-> Lambda may execute later.

-> To avoid inconsistency, Java copies the variable value.

-> If variable changes later, copied value and actual value may become different.

-> Therefore Java allows only final/effectively final variables.

---

# Memory Visualization

```text
main() starts
      ↓
int x = 10 created in stack
      ↓
Lambda captures x
      ↓
Java copies x value internally
      ↓
main() ends
      ↓
Original stack variable destroyed
      ↓
Lambda still uses copied value
```

---

# Internal Concept (Simplified)

Java internally behaves somewhat like this:

```java
int copiedValue = x;
```

-> Lambda uses copiedValue internally.

