# Closure with Anonymous Inner Class

Before Lambda Expressions, closures were commonly implemented using Anonymous Inner Classes.

Example:

```java
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int value = 50;

        Runnable r = new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                System.out.println(value);
            }
        };

        r.run();
    }
}
```

Output:

```text
50
```

---

# Closure with Lambda

```java
Runnable r = () -> {
    System.out.println(value);
};
```

-> Lambda version is shorter and cleaner.

---

# Closure in Streams API

Example:

```java
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int limit = 5;

        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1,2,3,4,5,6,7);

        list.stream()
            .filter(n -> n > limit)
            .forEach(System.out::println);
    }
}
```

Output:

```text
6
7
```

---

# Understanding Stream Closure

```java
.filter(n -> n > limit)
```

-> Lambda uses outer variable:

```java
limit
```

-> Lambda captures limit.

-> This is Closure.

---

# Closure in Multithreading

```java
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String message = "Thread Started";

        Thread t = new Thread(() -> {
            System.out.println(message);
        });

        t.start();
    }
}
```

-> Thread lambda captures outer variable 'message'.

-> This is another example of Closure.

---

# Difference Between Normal Function and Closure

| Normal Function             | Closure                        |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Uses only its own variables | Uses outer variables           |
| No memory of outer scope    | Remembers outer scope          |
| Independent execution       | Captures surrounding variables |
| No variable capture         | Variable capture exists        |

---

# Key Points to Remember

-> Closure captures variables from outer scope.

-> Lambda remembers outer variables.

-> Captured variables must be final or effectively final.

-> Java copies captured variables internally.

-> Closures are heavily used in functional programming.

-> Streams API uses closures extensively.

-> Anonymous inner classes also support closures.

---

# Common Interview Questions

## 1. What is Closure in Java?

-> A closure is a lambda or anonymous inner class that captures variables from its outer scope.

## 2. Why must variables be effectively final?

-> Because Java copies local variables internally for lambda usage.

-> Changing variables later may create inconsistency.

## 3. Does Java support true closures?

-> Java supports closure-like behavior using lambda expressions and anonymous inner classes.

## 4. Where are closures commonly used?

-> Streams API
-> Functional Programming
-> Multithreading
-> Event Handling
-> Callback Functions

---

# Technique to Remember

```text
Closure = Capture + Remember
```

-> Lambda captures outer variable.

-> Lambda remembers variable later.

---

# Final Conclusion

-> Closure in Java means a lambda or anonymous inner class can capture and remember variables from its surrounding scope.

-> Even after the outer method finishes execution, the lambda can still use those variables.

-> Java closures work only with final or effectively final variables to ensure safety and consistency.

-> Closures are one of the most important concepts behind Lambda Expressions, Streams API, and Functional Programming in Java.
